<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-23T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-23T19:00:00-05:00" n="460" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d460">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1322</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Francis</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-23T19:00:00-05:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">March 23, 1918, 7 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>21. Your 15 [13], March 16,<note n="1" xml:id="d460fn1">Not printed;
                                    discusses, as does No. 17, the Ambassador’s press declaration
                                    opposing a separate peace.</note> and 17, March 18.<note n="2" xml:id="d460fn2">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_402">p.
                                    402</ref>.</note> Department believes your action has had good
                                effect, but does not desire to modify in any way previous
                                instructions as to recognition of Soviet government. As conditions
                                change so rapidly Department has issued you only general
                                instructions and relies on your discretion and judgment to determine
                                your movements and matters not affecting policy of this Government.
                                Unhappily, the United States is unable to extend direct aid to the
                                people of Russia at this time but desires you to reflect attitude of
                                America as already conveyed to you in previous telegrams.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>